\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{ABSTRACT}
\section*{ABSTRACT}
This study aims to formulate a mathematical rating system for Men's NCAA Division 1 basketball teams, facilitating their ranking and aiding in the completion of the March Madness tournament bracket. Our focus encompasses all season games leading up to the tournament, with a particular emphasis on the significance of recent games, considering them most influential due to observed team improvement. Notably, our methodology involves negating the impact of home team advantage, as the games are hosted on neutral territories. Additionally, we prioritize acknowledging the advantage held by teams with ongoing win streaks over those with low to zero streaks.

We examine the frequency of records in a series of real numbers, x1, x2, x3 · · · where
any xi maybe 1 with the probability of p and 0 with the probability of 1−p = q. A record
is, in this paper, defined as a streak of 1s that is longer than any of the previous streaks.
Formulas are deduced for the probability that the first record ends at any given index
and that any given nth record is of length l. Expected values are then calculated. These
formulas can be used to analyze if records in sequences are the results of randomness or
indicate underlying trends.

This project involves collaborative efforts within groups to design and implement a unique scheme for rating and ranking NCAA Division 1 men's college basketball teams based on the data from the 2023-2024 season. Participants will employ analytical methods and statistical approaches to calculate their team rankings, and subsequently utilize these rankings to complete an NCAA tournament bracket. The project culminates in a competition where the effectiveness of each group's rating scheme will be evaluated to determine the most successful methodology for predicting team performance in the tournament. Through this hands-on exercise, participants will gain practical experience in building and assessing ranking systems for collegiate sports, fostering a deeper understanding of the dynamics within NCAA Division 1 men's college basketball. (add more info)



